node.text:
Next up in the profile series in order of size (as long as you include the circumference of her head) is Kitty. Kitty was an "accident". (Ironically she also happens to have some "accidents" but we'll get to that part in a minute.) The inn at Wolfgang2242 was full up with dogs when she appeared at my door as part of the senior dog promotions I do for the Maxfund Animal Adoption Center. Out of the 5 years or so that I've been doing these promotions, Kitty is the only one that didn't end up with any applications. I'm sure it's because she is incontinent. That's probably due to a spinal injury, but for whatever the reason, she can't always control her on/off valve. When I found out she was still at Maxfund several weeks after the promotion, I asked if I could take her home for the holidays, and then of course it was all over. I officially adopted her shortly after that.

When you pick up Kitty, kiss her, and tell her how cute she is, she gets so tickled by the attention that she pees in delight. I mean, you kinda gotta take that as a compliment.  If we are outside and she's not wearing a diaper, I've learned to bend at the waist and hold her out far enough to prevent shoe splatters. If we're in public it looks a little ridiculous, but you know, you do what you gotta do. 

 Kitty's personality is demanding, aloof and goofy. Whereas the other dogs are good with some alone time,  Kitty wants to be with me every minute. I take her with me as much as I can, but when I can't she becomes momentarily aloof. "Well I didn't really want to be with you anyway." When she's in an extra good mood, usually right before bed,  she becomes a little white speed ball, racing around the yard and up the stairs, prancing around at the top of the landing like a pent up show pony. Even though I'm always second place in this race, the laughter is worth the  loss. 

Likes: maximum absorbency 

Dislikes:  when cats answer to her name 

Goals:  never ever lose the race to bed.

Nickname:  Kitty Kitty Bang Bang

node.text:
Next up on the profile series, in the order of size, is my one-eyed, two- toothed, slave to fashion, Willamina. She came to me from @truefaithfulpetrescuemission in Florida who pulled her from the Miami Dade shelter. She sadly received no interested offers to adopt so I adopted her about 2 years ago. (first pic) She's guessed to be about 16 years old. We aren't sure what happened to the missing eye but even the remaining eye just barely sees, and the two teeth she has left on the bottom are strictly for show since her bottom jaw has mostly disintegrated. But Willamina is a dog that doesn't let anything hold her back. She's like one of those surfers that gets a leg bitten off by a shark and gets right back in the water the next day.  She's absolutely fearless. 

The hair on her body is very thin so during the 1st few days here in the winter I always made sure she had something to wear. (swipe right) It soon became apparent that she was meant for wearing clothes and her wardrobe took on a life of it's own. Clothes to wear to a dance club, clothes to wear to the beach, to the library, to an archeological excavation, to climb Mount Evans, a night at the opera with Pavarotti, you name it, she has it. Over the years @truefathfulpetrescue  and others have sent her stuff to wear, and I might have done a little online shopping myself after a few whiskies on the weekends. (Don't get distracted by that sad picture of an elderly man drunk shopping for dog clothes on the weekends; this post is about  Willamina.)

She is always on alert. When one of the other dogs (that can actually see) sound the alarm about something in the yard, Willamena is the first to chime in.  She doesn't know what she is barking about, but by God she's gonna make sure everyone in the else in the house knows about the unseen, impending danger. You never know when one of those leg biting sharks will appear. 

Breed: Rescue. (possibly a Maltese mix for you sticklers.) 

Likes:  Fashion week in Milan, soft food, retro hair barrettes.
Dislikes:  Off the rack.
Goals:  To grow that other eye back.
Nickname: Willamena ballerina jalapena. (are you sensing a trend from the previous profile?)

node.text:
Because of many follower requests and some prodding from my neighbor, I've decided to do a short series in the next few weeks that features each of the dogs with a little bit of information about them and where they came from.  I've done this before but it's been a few years and of course the dogs have changed and there are some new people on the account.
So, beginning with the smallest and working my way up, this feature is dedicated to 12 yr old Fernando.
Fernando came to me from Puerto Rico through @strayfromtheheart rescue group.  For the first 11 years of his life Fernando lived in a cage and was used for breeding purposes.  Before meeting him, I figured his history would have some negative effects on his personality and ability to trust, but nothing could be further from the truth.  He is as sweet and as personable as any dog I've ever met.  I mean he does have his issues from living in a cage, like he absolutely refuses to be housebroken.  I mean not even a TINY hint of an interest in picking up that habit.  So, he wears a belly band during the day and it's hardly even a thought anymore. 
For some odd reason almost as soon as he arrived he fell in love with Melvin, a dachshund that at 18 is the oldest dog in the house.  I can almost always find him laying on top of Melvin or cleaning his face or following him around like an obsessed super fan that's only days away of receiving a restraining order. 
Fernando has to be carried up and down the stairs but he uses the doggy door like a pro.  Yeah I know, somehow he manages to go in and out and STILL not notice the other dogs peeing out there. 😁
Likes:  super old dachshunds
Dislikes: conversations about potty training
Goals:  to pee on everything in the house.  Luckily with the belly band he can achieve this goal with my approval.  It's a win/win
Nickname: Fernando bandito mosquito torpedo

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by Steve Greig on July 11, 2021 tagging @maxfund. May be an image of Maltese.

node.text:
See that handsome, muscular, brute of a dog?  No, not Fernando! That beautiful bulldog sitting next to him. Well, his name is Buddha and Buddha needs a home. I work with the Maxfund Rescue group in Denver to help them find homes for senior dogs and dogs with disabilities. Buddha is a 10 year old, perfectly healthy, bulldog that needs to find his forever family. His original family took him to Maxfund when they had a baby and thought they could no longer care for him. 🙄 Then, he was adopted out and returned by someone for reasons that are kind of hard to explain. It sounds like they had another dog they favored over Buddha which caused Buddha anxiety and that led to weight loss, and and it just didn't end up being a healthy situation for anyone. So he's back again and up for adoption. He does well in play groups at Maxfund with other dogs and is overall the happy photogenic guy you see in these pictures. He's one of those dogs that isn't actually that interested in other dogs although there is a 3 legged bulldog at Maxfund that he's fond of playing with.

If you are interested in giving Buddha a forever home call Maxfund at 303.595.4917 to set up an appointment to meet him, or email Kim at kimberlyalisonshively@gmail 
#maxfundsenioradoption
